entry.title: [android/passwords] Check local UPM pref in features_util
entry.content:
Migrate the last kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage production check to

CanCreateAccountStore() and delete the flag. Behavior changes only

behind flag (Before this CL, functions like IsOptedInForAccountStorage()

returned false on Android because the kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage

flag was disabled. Now they continue to return false because they check

the local UPM pref - via CanCreateAccountStore(PrefService*) - and that

is always kOff when the local UPM flag is disabled).



Tests that used override kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage are fixed in a

number of different ways.



1. credential_manager_impl_unittest: CredentialManagerImpl only depends

on the nullness of PasswordManagerClient::GetAccountStore(). The

suite uses a mock client and is already parameterized to test both

cases. So just remove the flag override.

2. password_manager_features_util_unittest: The tests for the touched

logic. Set the UPM pref respectively to kOff/kOn in the

WithoutAccountStorageTest/WithAccountStorageTest suites. The first

is #ifdefed to Android, since it cannot pass on other platforms,

where CanCreateAccountStore() is unconditionally true.

3. form_fetcher_impl_unittest: Same as (1).

4. http_auth_manager_unittest: Same as (1).

5. password_feature_manager_impl_unittest: PasswordFeatureManagerImpl

calls the features_util functions, so this is the same as (2).

6. password_manager_client_helper_unittest: PasswordManagerClientHelper

depends on PasswordFeatureManager and its methods are already mocked

accordingly in each test. Just remove the flag overrides. The test

NoPromptToMoveWithoutFeature is removed because it's essentially a

dupe of NoPromptToMoveForNonOptedInUser, as the flag wasn't directly

checked.

7. password_manager_unittest: PasswordManager uses a bunch of real

objects, including a PasswordFeatureManagerImpl, so same as (5)/(2).

8. password_receiver_service_impl_unittest: PasswordReceiverImpl is

injected with the account store on construction, which can be null or

not, and the parameterized suite already tests both cases. It also

invokes features_util functions, so requires the setup from (2).

9. store_metrics_reporter_unittest: Invokes features_util functions, so

same as (2).

entry.title: Event Timing reports EventTarget for more pointer events
entry.content:
Only in cases where there is not a single pointer event registered on a page, blink may entirely optimize out EventDispatch steps, since there are no observers anyway. This optimization should not normally be detectable.



However, the Event Timing API still measures these events and reports them to the performance timeline. Because the EventDispatch steps are where we assign EventTarget to Event objects, the Event Timing API was effectively missing the target value whenever we skipped this step.



This patch plumbs the original HitTest target which we fall back to under such situations.

entry.title: [QuickStart]: Fix QuickStartController::AbortFlow() cycle after cancel
entry.content:
This CL adds a Step::FLOW_ABORTED to fix an AbortFlow() cycle in the

QS Controller. Previously when a user cancelled, the QS Controller

aborted the flow, closed the connection, and reset state. Inside

ConnectionLifecycleListener::OnConnectionClosed(), observers were

This addresses several issues around WebUI help bubble focus:

toast.

promo bubble.

entry.title: [Gardening] Revert "Lacros testing: Make browser init param overriding more robust"
entry.content:
This reverts commit e5f6f1434e631cd1c8154a41ee95ce6126688e9a.



Reason for revert: Appears to be causing content_browsertests

failures.



Original change's description:

> Lacros testing: Make browser init param overriding more robust

>

> See chromium:1508245 for context.

>

> - Decide whether crosapi is enabled based on the command line

> switches. In particular, make it independent of when/whether

> BrowserTestBase::SetUp gets called.

> We still provide DisableCrosapiForTesting for legacy reasons,

> as some tests need to ovrerride it.

>

> - This, plus some new checks, make it hard for tests

> * to accidentally and silently override the Ash-provided init

> params with mostly empty ones, or

> * to accidentally and silently prevent the Ash-provided params

> from even being read.

>

> - Address a TODO in InProcessBrowserTest thanks to these changes.

>

> - Call DisableCrosapiForTesting in ViewsTestBase-derived tests that

> run with crosapi enabled but are not prepared to set it up (and thus

> would fail one of the new checks) and in fact don't need crosapi.

>

> - Remove InProcessBrowserTest::IsCrosapiEnabled() in favor of

> !chromeos::BrowserParamsProxy::IsCrosapiDisabledForTesting(). There

> is no need to have the InProcessBrowserTest predicate and it's not

> an InProcessBrowserTest level concept.

>

> - Remove ScopedDisableCrosapiForTesting class, as there is no need for

> a scope. Tests should either not call DisableCrosapiForTesting at

> all or should do it very early on (CHECK'd). Undoing it is not

> supported and it's not neceesary because tests run in separate

> processes.

>

> - Add documentation to startup/README.md.

>

> - Remove some uses of IsCrosapiDisabledForTesting from production code

> that are no longer needed.

>

entry.title: [UNO] Small fixes in `DiceWebSigninInterceptor`
entry.content:
- `OnInterceptionReadyToBeProcessed()` did an early check if the user

has declined profile creation. Some of the interception bubble might

have skipped due to that check even though they don't require the

creation of a new profile (e.g. Chrome sign in bubble)

- `ShouldEnforceEnterpriseProfileSeparation()` in case of a reauth, it

doesn't check if the account is managed and returns true if the

profile hasn't accepted management. This CL ensure that this doesn't

return true if the account is not managed.

- For managed sync users, the management consent is implicit. The

current code sets the profile management and cancels the interception.

It is more correct to set the bit and check if other type of

interception should apply. Note: There are other places where the

management bit is set for sync managed users. It is unclear if setting

this bit in the interception logic is needed.

- `GetHeuristicOutCome()` returns null if there potentially the account

is subject to interception and it couldn't decide based on the

available information. On `ShouldShowChromeSigninBubbleWithReason::

kShouldNotShowUnknownAccessPoint`, `GetHeuristicOutcome()` returns

null which gives the wrong impression that the access point might be

known later when interception is ready to be processed. This condition

is removed to simplify the code, remove confusion and potentially show

other bubbles if appropriate (e.g. save password).
